function GUIDE_SECTIONS(){return[
{title:'What is Mead?',icon:'🍯',content:'Mead is the world\'s oldest alcoholic beverage — fermented honey, water, and yeast. Evidence dates back to 7000 BCE. It predates wine and beer.\n\nMead ranges from bone-dry to lusciously sweet, still to sparkling, 5% to 20% ABV. Variants include Melomel (with fruit), Cyser (with apples), Metheglin (with spices), Bochet (caramelized honey), and Sack (very sweet, high ABV).\n\nThe default setup runs a 3-stage vessel pipeline (9 L primary → 7.6 L or 5 L secondary → 5 L bulk aging) and targets 5 L final volume per batch — roughly 6×750ml + 2×500ml of finished mead.\n\nEvery recipe in this app pitches a commercial yeast strain — but that\'s a modern convenience, not a requirement. Raw, unprocessed honey and the air around it already carry wild yeast, and mead can ferment with none added at all: the historically authentic approach, sometimes called "Viking mead". It\'s genuinely riskier — cap the OG around 1.070 (roughly 900g honey per 5L) since a wild population can\'t reliably outcompete contamination at higher gravity, expect a slower and less predictable start, and stir often to keep the wild yeast active and discourage anything unwanted from settling. Worth trying once a few normal batches are under your belt, not as a first batch.'},
{title:'Your Equipment',icon:'⚗',content:'Vessel fleet (6 total, 3 sizes):\n• 2× 9 L wide-mouth — primary fermenters (vigorous fermentation with healthy headspace)\n• 2× 7.6 L wide-mouth — secondary / assist fermenters (racking, clarification, backup)\n• 2× 5 L wide-mouth — bulk aging before bottling (minimal headspace, oxidation-protected)\n\nWide-mouth vessels are preferred for mead — easier to clean, easier to add fruit/spices, easier to stir vigorously for nutrient additions. Glass over plastic for any vessel held more than a few weeks — see "Choosing Fermenter Material" below for the full trade-offs.\n\nAirlock: Fill with water or vodka to the line. Bubbling frequency indicates fermentation activity.\n\nHydrometer + trial jar: Measures specific gravity. Read at the bottom of the meniscus.\n\nAuto-siphon: Transfers mead between vessels without disturbing sediment.\n\nLong stainless spoon (60 cm): for stirring and degassing.\n\nMuslin / cheesecloth bags: Hold spices and fruits for easy removal.'},
{title:'Choosing Fermenter Material',icon:'🪣',content:'Bucket, glass, PET or steel — every material trades off the same five things differently: oxygen permeability, breakage/injury risk, weight, visibility, and cost. None wins on all five. The right choice depends on the STAGE, not one "best" vessel — this is the deep-dive behind the one-line rule in "Your Equipment".\n\n━━ FOOD-GRADE PLASTIC BUCKET (HDPE) ━━\nCheapest, lightest, widest mouth — easiest to clean and to add fruit/spices through. Opaque, so you can only check on the mead by lifting the lid.\nWeak point: HDPE is slightly oxygen-permeable, and cleaning brushes leave scratches that become permanent grooves over years of reuse — a real place for bacteria/biofilm to hide that no amount of sanitizer fully reaches. Retire scratched buckets rather than trusting them for long jobs.\nBest for: PRIMARY fermentation only. The thick CO₂ blanket during vigorous primary largely covers for the slight permeability, and buckets get replaced from wear long before oxygen ingress would matter.\n\n━━ GLASS CARBOY (DEMIJOHN) ━━\nCompletely impermeable to oxygen — the benchmark for long aging. See-through, so you can watch fermentation and spot problems early. Doesn\'t stain, doesn\'t retain odours, smooth non-porous surface that\'s genuinely easy to get clean.\nWeak point: heavy, and it breaks. A full 19 L glass carboy is a real, well-documented injury risk in this hobby — wet glass plus an awkward two-handed lift is how people end up with serious lacerations. The narrow neck is also awkward to clean and to pass solid fruit or spice bags through.\nBest for: SECONDARY and BULK AGING, where zero oxygen permeability over months matters more than the handling risk — as long as it\'s lifted with care (see the safety note below).\n\n━━ PET PLASTIC CARBOY (E.G. "BETTER BOTTLE") ━━\nThe middle ground: much lighter and effectively unbreakable next to glass, still see-through, still a narrow neck like glass.\nWeak point: not fully oxygen-impermeable — it lets oxygen through slowly over many months, more than glass or steel does. Scratches over years of use too, just more slowly than a bucket since the surface is smoother.\nBest for: SECONDARY fermentation and bulk aging runs of a few months, where glass-like visibility without the breakage risk is worth more than the last word in oxygen-tightness. For something meant to sit 1-2+ years, glass or steel still has the edge.\n\n━━ STAINLESS STEEL (BREW BUCKET / CONICAL / KEG) ━━\nThe premium option: zero oxygen permeability, unbreakable, doesn\'t stain or carry flavour/odour between batches, easiest of all to clean and sanitize thoroughly.\nWeak point: expensive, heavy, and opaque — no sight glass, so you\'re reading gravity and airlock activity rather than watching the mead directly. Buying used or dented stainless is a false economy — a scratched or dented interior surface defeats the whole point of the material.\nBest for: brewers running several batches in parallel who\'ve outgrown the cost-per-batch of glass or PET, or anyone specifically eliminating breakage risk in a shared or family space. Not usually a first purchase.\n\n━━ WHICH ONE, WHEN? ━━\n• Primary: bucket or PET — durability and easy cleaning matter far more here than oxygen-tightness, since the CO₂ blanket already protects you.\n• Secondary: glass or PET — visibility helps catch clarity and other problems early.\n• Bulk aging (the long haul): glass or steel — this is the stage where oxygen permeability genuinely matters, since a mead can sit here a year or more.\n• Bottling: glass bottles, standard regardless of what it fermented in.\n\n━━ A REAL SAFETY NOTE ━━\nGlass carboy injuries are common enough in the hobby that plenty of experienced brewers switch to a bucket-with-spigot or PET specifically to remove the risk — not because the plastic ferments any better, it\'s a genuine trade-off between oxygen protection and physical safety. If using glass: never lift a full one by the neck alone, keep it low and close to the body while moving it, and consider a carboy handle/collar or moving it partway-full rather than topped all the way off.\n\n━━ WHAT TO ACTUALLY START WITH ━━\nOne food-grade bucket for primary plus a smaller glass or PET vessel for secondary/aging covers a first batch completely — this app\'s own default fleet (see "Your Equipment") is exactly that pattern scaled to three sizes. Stainless is an "I know I\'m keeping this hobby up" upgrade, not a starting requirement.'},
{title:'Vessel Staging Strategy',icon:'🪜',content:'Each batch flows through three vessel sizes — each phase optimized for what the mead needs at that moment.\n\n━━ STAGE 1 · Primary fermentation · 9 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill: ~7 L of must into the 9 L vessel (78% fill).\nWhy: Vigorous primary fermentation produces foam, CO₂, and krausen. The 22% headspace absorbs that activity without blow-off. Wide mouth lets you stir nutrients and degas vigorously.\nDuration: ~2-3 weeks, until gravity stabilizes near FG.\n\n━━ STAGE 2 · Secondary fermentation · 7.6 L or 5 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill: Rack off the gross lees from primary into a secondary vessel. Expect ~10% volume loss to lees and racking. Use the 7.6 L when you need flexibility (room for fruit additions, dry-hopping, oak); use the 5 L when you can fit (less headspace = better protection).\nWhy: Slow secondary fermentation continues, suspended yeast settles, the mead clears. Less aggressive than primary, so less headspace is needed.\nDuration: 2-6 weeks depending on style.\n\n━━ STAGE 3 · Bulk aging · 5 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill: Rack into a 5 L vessel filled as close to the neck as possible (>95% fill, minimal headspace). Top up with cooled boiled water or use glass marbles if needed.\nWhy: Long-term aging is enemy #1 of oxygen. The 5 L vessel — filled high — keeps oxygen exposure minimal. Time at this stage develops the mead\'s mature character.\nDuration: 3 months to 2+ years depending on style.\n\n━━ STAGE 4 · Bottling ━━\nRack from the 5 L bulk vessel directly into sanitized bottles. Expect ~5 L of finished mead = 6×750ml + 2×500ml (or 10×500ml). Cap, label, store in box with a printed storage label for tracking.\n\nThe 7.6 L vessels also serve as backup / assist — handy when running multiple batches in parallel, or for clarification stages where you want to rack twice.'},
{title:'Your Chemicals',icon:'🧪',content:'Chemipro OXI: Oxygen-based CLEANER. 4g per liter warm water, 2-5 min contact, drain well — strips organic residue, mead deposits, soap scum. Use FIRST to physically clean.\n\nChemipro SAN: Acid-anionic SANITIZER (no-rinse when drained). 2 ml per 1L water (= 20 ml per 10L). 1 minute contact on surface or 15-min soak. Foam is harmless. NOT for aluminum. NEVER mix with chlorine cleaners.\n\nStar San: the Five Star equivalent — phosphoric-acid based, no-rinse. 1.5 ml per 1L water, 1-2 min wet contact. Foam is harmless ("don\'t fear the foam"). The mixed solution keeps for weeks when made with distilled/RO water and the pH stays ≤ 3.\n\nEither sanitizer works — pick whichever you can buy locally and set it in Settings → Costs & Supplies.\n\nWorkflow: Clean with Chemipro OXI → drain → sanitize → drain → use. Both steps touch EVERYTHING that touches mead.\n\nPotassium Metabisulfite (Campden): Neutralizes chlorine, prevents oxidation after racking, stabilizes before bottling. 0.5g per 4.5L.\n\nPotassium Sorbate (Sorbistat): Stops yeast reproduction before back-sweetening. 1g per 4.5L. ALWAYS combine with metabisulfite — never alone.'},
{title:"M05 Mead Yeast",icon:'✦',content:"Mangrove Jack's M05 is engineered for mead. Properties:\n\n• Attenuation 95-100% — ferments very dry\n• Alcohol tolerance 18% — won\'t die early\n• Flocculation high — clears naturally\n• Temperature 15-30°C — ferment at 18°C for floral character, 24°C for faster but more neutral\n• One 10g packet covers 17L\n• Sprinkle directly on must surface\n• Store packets refrigerated"},
{title:'Yeast Nutrients (SNA / TOSNA)',icon:'⚡',content:'Honey is nutritionally poor. Without enough nutrient: stalled fermentation, hydrogen sulfide (rotten egg), harsh off-flavors. But the fix isn\'t "add it all up front" either — a big single dose triggers a yeast feeding frenzy, fermentation suddenly speeds up, and since fermentation is exothermic that spikes the must\'s own temperature and drives out more fusel alcohols (the hot, solventy, "jet fuel" taste in a young mead). Staggering the same total nutrient across several smaller doses avoids both failure modes — starving late, and overheating/fusel-ing early — not just one of them.\n\nTwo protocols, two products in your supply chain:\n\nSNA (Staggered Nutrient Addition):\n• Mangrove Jack\'s Mead Yeast Nutrient or Vinoferm Nutrivit — balanced DAP + amino blend\n• Day 1: Half the dose. Day 3: Remaining half.\n• High-gravity batches (OG > 1.110): Use double dose in three additions on days 1, 3, 7.\n• Default for most batches — simple and reliable.\n\nTOSNA (Pure-organic, staggered over 4 doses):\n• Fermaid-O — pure organic nitrogen\n• Go-Ferm rehydration, then 4 organic doses at +24h / +48h / +72h / +96h (or the 1/3 sugar break, whichever comes first)\n• Cleaner profile, slower fermentation, fewer off-flavors\n• Best for delicate styles where you want the honey to shine\n\nUse the TOSNA Planner in Brewing Tools to calculate doses for any active batch and apply the schedule with one click.'},
{title:'Gravity & ABV',icon:'📊',content:'Specific gravity (SG) measures how much denser your liquid is than water (1.000). Honey water reads 1.080-1.140.\n\nABV = (OG - FG) × 131.25\nExample: OG 1.098, FG 1.010 → 11.5% ABV\n\nHydrometer:\n• Read at the bottom of the meniscus\n• Calibrated at 20°C — use the Hydrometer Temp Correction tool when reading at other temperatures\n• Always sanitize before use\n• Degas the SAMPLE first, not just the batch — dissolved CO₂ clings to the hydrometer as tiny bubbles and floats it artificially high, which reads as a HIGHER (less-fermented-looking) gravity than the truth. Pour the sample between two glasses a few times, or give it a good stir/swirl, until the fizzing stops before reading. A reading taken right after vigorous fermentation without degassing first is the classic false "it hasn\'t moved" scare.\n\nRefractometer note: refractometers read Brix, not SG. The SG ↔ Brix converter in Brewing Tools handles conversion + the alcohol-skew correction needed once fermentation is underway.\n\nA stuck fermentation (gravity not dropping for 3+ days at temperature) needs intervention: warmer temp, fresh nutrient, or repitch.'},
{title:'Fermentation Stages',icon:'🔄',content:'Lag (0-24h): Yeast acclimatize. No visible activity is normal.\n\nPrimary (1-14 days): Vigorous bubbling, CO2 production, gravity drops 50-70%. Mead is cloudy. Vessel: 9 L primary.\n\nSecondary (weeks 2-6): Slow bubbling, gravity stabilizes, yeast flocculate, clarity improves. Rack from 9 L → 7.6 L or 5 L secondary.\n\nConditioning (1-3 months): Flavors integrate, harsh notes soften, dramatic clarity improvement. Often happens in the 5 L bulk aging vessel.\n\nAging (3-12+ months): True transformation. Where mead becomes excellent. Keep in 5 L bulk aging vessel with minimal headspace.'},
{title:'Troubleshooting',icon:'🔧',content:'No fermentation after 48h: Check temperature, verify yeast wasn\'t cooked, add nutrient, swirl gently.\n\nRotten egg smell: Stressed yeast. Stir vigorously to degas, add nutrient, raise temp slightly.\n\nStuck fermentation: Warm to 22-24°C, add nutrient, repitch fresh M05 in rehydrated form.\n\nCloudy mead: Normal during fermentation. Cold crash (2 weeks at 2-4°C) drops most haze. Bentonite for stubborn cases.\n\nToo dry: Stabilize with sorbate + metabisulfite, wait 24h, then back-sweeten with honey to taste.\n\nOff-flavors persist past 3 months: Likely contamination. Document and start over with better sanitation.'},
{title:'Headspace by Stage',icon:'📐',content:'Different stages want different headspace. The 3-vessel staged setup lets you match each phase.\n\n━━ Primary (9 L vessel) ━━\nFill to ~7 L (78% full). Leaves 2 L of headspace for foam, krausen, and CO₂ blow-off during vigorous primary fermentation. Wider headspace is forgiving — under-filling here is safer than over-filling.\n\n━━ Secondary (7.6 L or 5 L vessel) ━━\nFill: After racking from primary, you\'ll have ~6 L (with ~1 L lost to lees). A 7.6 L secondary at 80% fill is ideal during active secondary; or rack directly into a 5 L vessel (~95% fill) if secondary fermentation is nearly done.\n\n━━ Bulk aging (5 L vessel) ━━\nFill as close to 100% as possible. Top up with cooled boiled water if needed, or use sanitized glass marbles. Oxygen exposure during aging is the enemy of aromatics — minimal headspace is everything here.\n\nGENERAL RULES:\n• Primary NEEDS headspace (foam, CO₂, krausen).\n• Secondary WANTS less headspace (oxidation begins to matter).\n• Bulk aging DEMANDS minimal headspace (oxygen = enemy of aromatics).\n• Always rack gently under the surface — no splashing.\n• Add 0.5 g potassium metabisulfite at each racking stage to suppress oxidation.'},
{title:'Bottling',icon:'🍾',content:'When to bottle: Two identical gravity readings 3-7 days apart at target FG. Clear, mature flavor.\n\nProcess: Clean bottles & caps with Chemipro OXI, then sanitize with your no-rinse sanitizer (Chemipro SAN 2 ml/L or Star San 1.5 ml/L). Siphon (don\'t pour) into bottles. Leave minimal headspace (~1.5cm). Cap immediately.\n\nUse the guided bottling workflow in the batch view — it walks you through pre-flight, gravity check, sanitize timer, fill, label preview, and final save.\n\nLabel each bottle: Batch name, date bottled, OG/FG, ABV, batch number. Use the bottle label download for printable labels.\n\nStorage: Upright 2 weeks (lets cork seat or cap settle), then horizontal for cork bottles, upright for cap bottles. Cool, dark, stable temperature. Print a storage label for each box — it shows batch identity, contents, drinking window, and a QR code linking back to this app.\n\nClear vs amber glass: Clear shows off color (good for melomels). Amber protects delicate aromatics (good for spiced/traditional).'},
{title:'Sparkling & Carbonated Mead',icon:'🍾',content:'A sparkling mead carries dissolved CO₂ — from a gentle pétillant fizz to full champagne-style bubbles. There are two routes, and one rule that beats everything: you can only naturally carbonate a mead that can still referment.\n\n━━ THE GOLDEN RULE ━━\nBottle conditioning makes bubbles by feeding a small, measured dose of sugar to live yeast in a sealed bottle. So you must NOT have stabilized: potassium sorbate + sulfite stop yeast from reproducing, and a stabilized mead will never carbonate naturally. Decide on sparkling BEFORE you stabilize. If you already sorbated, your only route is forced carbonation in a keg.\n\n━━ FERMENT IT OUT FIRST ━━\nThe mead must be fully fermented to a stable final gravity (two identical readings several days apart) BEFORE priming. Leftover unfermented sugar + priming sugar + a sealed bottle = over-pressure and broken glass. Prime a finished mead with exactly the sugar the calculator specifies — never a rough scoop.\n\n━━ TARGET CARBONATION (CO₂ volumes) ━━\n• Still: under 0.5\n• Lightly sparkling / pétillant: ~1.5–2.0\n• Sparkling: ~2.5\n• Highly sparkling: ~3.0\n• Champagne-style: ~3.5–4.0\nHigher target = more pressure = stronger bottles required.\n\n━━ METHOD 1 · BOTTLE CONDITIONING (priming) ━━\n1. Confirm fermentation is finished and the mead is NOT stabilized.\n2. Use Brewing Tools → Carbonation / Priming Sugar for the exact dose from your volume, temperature and target.\n3. Dissolve the sugar in a little warm water, gently mix it into the whole batch (no splashing — avoid oxygen), then bottle.\n4. Cap in pressure-rated bottles and condition 2–3 weeks at 18–22°C so the yeast eats the priming sugar.\n5. Chill before serving — cold holds the CO₂ and settles the yeast.\n\n━━ METHOD 2 · FORCED CARBONATION (keg) ━━\nWith a corny keg you carbonate under CO₂ pressure instead of yeast: chill the mead, set the regulator to the pressure for your target volumes at that temperature, and wait a few days (or shake-carbonate faster). No live yeast needed — this is the only option for an already-stabilized mead.\n\n━━ BOTTLES & CLOSURES (safety) ━━\nStill-wine bottles are NOT pressure-rated — never use them for sparkling. Use:\n• Champagne / Belgian heavy bottles with crown caps, or corks held by a wire muselet/agrafe.\n• Swing-top (Grolsch) or heavy beer bottles for lower carbonation (up to ~2.5 vol).\nKeep one clear PET tester bottle — squeeze it to feel when the pressure has built. Condition the bottles inside a closed tub or box, just in case one fails.\n\n━━ CLEARING THE YEAST (optional) ━━\nBottle-conditioned mead leaves a fine yeast layer. Either pour gently and leave the last splash behind (pétillant naturel style), or — for crystal-clear champagne-style — riddle (tilt neck-down over days) and disgorge the frozen plug, then top up and re-cork. Most home meadmakers simply pour carefully.\n\nSee Brewing Tools → Carbonation / Priming Sugar for the exact sugar dose and a pressure-safety check.'}
];}

// ==================== CIDER GUIDE ====================
// Cider's counterpart to BEGINNER_HOWTO/GUIDE_SECTIONS above — same structure
// and depth, genuinely rewritten for cider rather than a word-swap (different
// yeasts, different typical OG/timelines, LARS apple chemistry has no mead
// equivalent at all).
var CIDER_BEGINNER_HOWTO=[
  {t:'Gather your kit',d:'A fermenter with an airlock, a hydrometer + trial jar, an auto-siphon, a long spoon, and a no-rinse sanitiser. For a first 5 L batch: ~5 L fresh or 100% apple juice with no preservatives/sorbate, a packet of cider yeast (e.g. Lallemand Nottingham), pectic enzyme, and yeast nutrient (Fermaid-O).'},
  {t:'Clean, then sanitise',d:'Clean everything that will touch the juice with an oxygen cleaner, then sanitise with a no-rinse acid sanitiser (Chemipro SAN or Star San). Cider skips the honey-dissolving step mead needs — but sanitation matters just as much, arguably more given cider\'s greater real-world vinegar (VA) risk.'},
  {t:'Check the juice & take OG',d:'Pour the juice straight into the sanitised fermenter — no mixing with water needed. Stir in the pectic enzyme (it prevents a lasting apple-pectin haze later). Take a hydrometer reading — that\'s your Original Gravity (OG), usually 1.045–1.065 for a standard-strength cider.'},
  {t:'Pitch the yeast',d:'Sprinkle dry cider yeast over the surface (or rehydrate per the packet). Seal with the airlock filled to the line, and keep it somewhere stable at 18–20 °C — cider yeasts like Nottingham are happy a few degrees cooler than mead\'s M05.'},
  {t:'Feed it (days 1–3)',d:'Apple juice varies in nitrogen more than honey must does, but treat it as needing help unless you know otherwise — add yeast nutrient in stages over the first few days, see the Nutrient Protocols guide. All nutrient goes in before the 1/3 sugar break, same rule as mead.'},
  {t:'Let it ferment',d:'Bubbling starts within a day and often finishes faster than mead — most standard ciders reach a stable gravity in 2–4 weeks rather than mead\'s typical 2–4+ weeks at higher gravities. Take a gravity reading every few days.'},
  {t:'Rack to secondary',d:'When gravity is stable, siphon the cider off the sediment (lees) into a clean vessel, leaving the gunk behind. This is also the decision point for some styles (e.g. English Cider\'s malolactic-or-stabilise choice) — see the Apple & Pear Library and Recipes for style-specific guidance.'},
  {t:'Age it — but check the style first',d:'Unlike mead, aging needs vary hugely by cider style. A Common Cider is genuinely ready to drink in a month; an English Cider or Applewine rewards 6–12+ months. Check the recipe\'s own aging window rather than assuming "longer is always better."'},
  {t:'Bottle',d:'Two identical gravity readings a few days apart mean it\'s done. Sanitise bottles, siphon in with minimal headspace, cap, and label with the batch, date, OG/FG and ABV. Traditional cider is very often sparkling — see Sparkling & Carbonated Cider below before you decide still vs. bottle-conditioned.'},
  {t:'Taste & learn',d:'Pour, observe, smell, taste — and write it down. Some ciders (Dry-Hopped, Common) are at their best within weeks; others keep improving for a year or more. Your notes are how the next batch — and the next apple blend — gets better.'}
];
function CIDER_GUIDE_SECTIONS(){return[
{title:'What is Cider?',icon:'🍎',content:'Cider is fermented apple juice — yeast turning apple sugar into alcohol, the same way mead ferments honey and wine ferments grapes. Traditional cider-growing regions (England\'s West Country, Normandy, Brittany, Asturias/the Basque Country, the northeastern US) have been making it for centuries, often from apples nobody would want to eat.\n\nCider ranges from bone-dry to dessert-sweet, still to fully sparkling, 4% to 12%+ ABV. This app\'s built-in library covers 13 distinct styles: Common Cider (culinary apples, everyday), Heirloom Cider (real cider-apple character), English Cider (Kingston Black, tannic, optionally malolactic), French Cider (low-ABV, wild-fermented, traditionally sweet), Spanish Cider/Sidra (rustic, wild, fully dry), New England Cider (raisins, higher ABV), Applewine (wine-strength, wine-yeast-driven), Ice Cider (freeze-concentrated, dessert-sweet), Fire Cider (caramelized maple, dessert-sweet), Fruit Cider, Spiced Cider, Experimental/Dry-Hopped Cider, and Perry (fermented pear juice — its own thing, not "cider with pears").\n\nThe defining technical idea in cider — one mead has no real equivalent for — is the LARS classification: apples are bittersweet, bittersharp, sharp, or sweet depending on their tannin and acid content, and real cider is usually a BLEND of these roles rather than a single variety. See "Apple & Pear Chemistry (LARS)" below and the Apple & Pear Library for the full picture.\n\nThe default setup runs the same 3-stage vessel pipeline as mead (9 L primary → 7.6 L or 5 L secondary → 5 L bulk aging) and targets 5 L final volume per batch.'},
{title:'Your Equipment',icon:'⚗',content:'The core kit is identical to mead\'s — a fermenter, airlock, hydrometer, auto-siphon and sanitiser don\'t care what they\'re fermenting. A few cider-specific notes:\n\nVessel fleet: same 3-size setup as mead (2× 9 L primary, 2× 7.6 L secondary/assist, 2× 5 L bulk aging). Wide-mouth vessels are just as useful for cider — easier to add fruit, spices, or hops, easier to stir in nutrient.\n\nFruit press (optional): only needed if you\'re pressing your own apples/pears rather than buying juice. A basic press + apple crusher/scratter is enough for small batches; most homebrewers start with store-bought fresh-pressed juice and skip this entirely.\n\nMuslin/straining bags: essential for cider more than mead — used to hold pomace if pressing your own, and to hold spice/hop/fruit additions in secondary for easy removal.\n\nPectic enzyme is arguably cider\'s single most important "equipment-adjacent" item — see Your Chemicals below.\n\nHydrometer + trial jar, auto-siphon, long stainless spoon: identical role and use to mead.'},
{title:'Vessel Staging Strategy',icon:'🪜',content:'The same three-vessel-size flow as mead applies to cider, just with generally faster timelines at standard-strength OGs.\n\n━━ STAGE 1 · Primary fermentation · 9 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill: ~7 L of juice into the 9 L vessel (78% fill) for a 5 L target batch scaled up, or match your recipe\'s actual volume.\nWhy: Primary fermentation is usually less violently foamy than a high-gravity mead, but still benefits from headspace, especially for high-OG styles (New England, Ice Cider, Fire Cider).\nDuration: Often just 1–3 weeks for standard-strength cider — noticeably faster than a typical mead.\n\n━━ STAGE 2 · Secondary fermentation · 7.6 L or 5 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill: Rack off the gross lees from primary. Use the 7.6 L when you need flexibility (fruit additions, dry-hopping, oak, or English Cider\'s malolactic decision point); use the 5 L when secondary is nearly finished.\nWhy: Continued clarification and, for some styles, the aroma-preserving fruit/spice/hop additions that overwhelmingly belong in secondary for cider (CO₂ off-gassing during primary scrubs delicate apple and adjunct aromatics).\nDuration: 1–8 weeks depending on style and whether you\'re pursuing malolactic fermentation.\n\n━━ STAGE 3 · Bulk aging · 5 L wide-mouth ━━\nFill as close to the neck as possible (>95% fill) — oxidation is exactly as much the enemy for cider as for mead.\nDuration: Wildly style-dependent — as little as 2–4 weeks for a Common Cider, a year or more for English Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider or Fire Cider. Check the specific recipe\'s aging window rather than assuming a universal "cider" answer.\n\n━━ STAGE 4 · Bottling ━━\nRack from the 5 L bulk vessel directly into sanitized bottles. Traditional cider is very often naturally sparkling — see Sparkling & Carbonated Cider before deciding.'},
{title:'Your Chemicals',icon:'🧪',content:'Cider uses the exact same cleaning/sanitizing/stabilizing chemicals as mead, plus one addition that matters far more here than it does for honey-based mead.\n\nPectic enzyme: THE cider-specific essential. Apple and pear juice are naturally loaded with pectin, and without breaking it down enzymatically, most ciders develop a persistent haze that gravity and time alone won\'t clear. Add at the start of primary (roughly 0.4 g/L, see individual recipes for exact doses) — it\'s cheap insurance against a whole batch staying cloudy.\n\nChemipro OXI: Oxygen-based CLEANER, same dose and role as mead (4 g/L warm water, 2-5 min contact).\n\nChemipro SAN / Star San: Acid-based SANITIZERS, same dose and role as mead.\n\nPotassium Metabisulfite (Campden): Same neutralizing/anti-oxidation/stabilizing role — but note it also suppresses malolactic bacteria, so for an English Cider pursuing MLF you deliberately withhold it until you\'ve decided the phenolic/buttery character has developed enough. For Perry, the opposite is true — add it PROMPTLY after fermentation, since perry\'s citric acid converts to vinegar-like acetic acid (not mead or apple cider\'s buttery MLF result) if malolactic bacteria are left unchecked.\n\nPotassium Sorbate (Sorbistat): Same role as mead — stops yeast reproduction before back-sweetening. ALWAYS combine with metabisulfite, never alone.'},
{title:'Cider Yeast',icon:'✦',content:'Lallemand Nottingham is cider\'s equivalent of mead\'s M05 — a safe, neutral, widely-used default that lets the apple character lead.\n\n• Attenuation high — ferments cleanly toward dry\n• Alcohol tolerance ~14% — plenty for most standard-strength ciders\n• Ferments happily cooler than most mead yeasts — 12–20°C, ideal around 18–20°C\n• An English ale-derived strain, budget-friendly, genuinely used by craft cideries\n• Sprinkle directly on juice surface\n\nOther cider strains worth knowing:\n• Mangrove Jack\'s M02 — Cider: another neutral, cider-purpose-built option, similar role to Nottingham (~12% tolerance)\n• Lallemand EC-1118: the highest-tolerance option (~18%) — the right choice for high-OG styles like New England Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider and Fire Cider, though it strips some delicate aroma\n• Lallemand 71B: softens sharp malic acid and boosts fruity esters — the standout pick for fruit ciders and heritage-apple blends where you want a rounder result\n• White Labs WLP775 (English Cider): the traditional liquid choice for English Cider specifically, supports the classic phenolic/buttery malolactic character\n\nWild/native fermentation: French Cider and Sidra are traditionally made with no yeast added at all, relying on the juice\'s own wild population — genuinely unpredictable but authentic. See those recipes\' own notes for the reliable-fallback alternative if you\'d rather not gamble a whole batch on it.'},
{title:'Yeast Nutrients (SNA / TOSNA)',icon:'⚡',content:'Apple and pear juice vary widely in natural nitrogen — some dessert-apple and heavily-filtered commercial juices run about as low as honey must, while bittersweets, fresh-pressed and orchard blends often carry real YAN of their own. Since you usually can\'t know which without a lab test, treating it as needing help is the safer default. Without enough nitrogen: stalled fermentation, hydrogen sulfide (rotten egg), harsh off-flavors — the same failure modes as an under-fed mead.\n\nThis app\'s built-in cider recipes standardize on a simple two-dose Fermaid-O schedule:\n\n• Dose 1: ~1–1.5 g/5 L once fermentation is visibly active (day 1)\n• Dose 2 (the remainder): at or before the 1/3 sugar break\n\nHigher-OG styles (New England Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider, Fire Cider) use a heavier total dose (~3 g/5 L) split the same way, since more fermentable sugar means more nitrogen demand.\n\nTwo styles — French Cider and Sidra — deliberately skip nutrient addition entirely. That\'s not an oversight: a slow, low-nitrogen wild fermentation is the whole point of those styles, preserving aromatics and residual sweetness that a fully-fed fermentation would ferment away.\n\nUse the TOSNA Planner in Brewing Tools to calculate doses for any active cider batch and apply the schedule with one click — like the mead version, it assumes the must itself contributes negligible nitrogen, which is the safer default when you don\'t know your juice\'s actual YAN.'},
{title:'Apple & Pear Chemistry (LARS)',icon:'📐',content:'This is cider\'s own body of knowledge — mead has no real equivalent, since a single honey variety doesn\'t need to be "blended for structure" the way cider apples do.\n\nThe Long Ashton Research Station (LARS) classification sorts apples into four categories by two measurements: tannin % and acid %.\n\n• Bittersweet (tannin >0.2%, acid ≤0.45%): the backbone of English-style cider. Dabinett and Yarlington Mill are classic examples — real structure, low sharpness.\n• Bittersharp (tannin >0.2%, acid >0.45%): the rarest and most prized category — genuine tannin AND acid together. Kingston Black and Foxwhelp are the benchmark examples, sometimes capable of standing alone as a single-varietal.\n• Sharp (tannin ≤0.2%, acid >0.45%): bright acid, little tannin. Most American heirlooms (Baldwin, Golden Russet) and common tart apples (Granny Smith, Bramley\'s Seedling) fall here.\n• Sweet (tannin ≤0.2%, acid ≤0.45%): mild, low-structure culinary and dessert apples — Golden Delicious, Gala, most supermarket apples. The base of most "juice from the store" cider, but needs blending with a sharp or bittersweet apple for real character.\n\nThe classic English blending approach: a bittersweet backbone (structure) + a sharp apple (brightness) in roughly 70:30 to 80:20 proportions — exactly the pattern this app\'s Heirloom, English, and New England Cider recipes follow.\n\nIMPORTANT: perry pears use a numerically similar-looking scale, but the actual thresholds and category feel are DIFFERENT — never compare a pear\'s tannin/acid numbers directly against an apple\'s. See the Apple & Pear Library for every variety in this app\'s database rated for tannin, acid, natural sugar (Brix), and which recipes use it.'},
{title:'Gravity & ABV',icon:'📊',content:'Specific gravity (SG) measures how much denser your liquid is than water (1.000). Fresh apple/pear juice typically reads 1.045–1.065; concentrated or adjunct-boosted musts (New England, Ice Cider, Fire Cider) can run much higher — 1.080 to 1.150+.\n\nABV = (OG - FG) × 131.25\nExample: OG 1.055, FG 1.005 → 6.6% ABV — a typical Common Cider.\n\nHydrometer: same technique as mead — read at the bottom of the meniscus, calibrated at 20°C, always sanitize before use, and degas the SAMPLE first (pour between two glasses a few times or swirl until the fizzing stops) — dissolved CO₂ clings to the hydrometer and floats it artificially high, reading as MORE sugar left than is actually true.\n\nA few cider-specific gravity notes:\n• Ice Cider and Fire Cider are deliberately STOPPED well short of dry with metabisulfite — a stable, sweet gravity is the intended endpoint, not a stall to fix.\n• Sidra and most standard ciders ferment fully dry (SG near 1.000) — that\'s expected, not a problem.\n• A stuck fermentation below a style\'s expected FG (not deliberately stopped) needs the same intervention as mead: warmer temp, fresh nutrient, or a repitch with EC-1118 for its higher tolerance.'},
{title:'Fermentation Stages',icon:'🔄',content:'Lag (0-24h): Yeast acclimatize. No visible activity is normal — wild-fermented styles (French Cider, Sidra) can take several days longer than an inoculated pitch.\n\nPrimary (3-14 days): Vigorous bubbling, gravity drops steadily. Standard-strength cider often moves through primary faster than an equivalent-OG mead. Vessel: 9 L primary.\n\nSecondary (1-8 weeks): Slower activity, clarification begins, and — for styles that use it — fruit/spice/hop additions go in here specifically to preserve fresh aroma. Rack from 9 L → 7.6 L or 5 L secondary.\n\nConditioning (2-8 weeks): Flavors integrate, pectin haze (if under control) continues clearing. Often happens in the 5 L bulk aging vessel.\n\nAging (varies hugely by style): A Common Cider is essentially done here after a few more weeks. An English Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider or Fire Cider is just getting started — true transformation can take 6-12+ months. Check the specific recipe rather than assuming.'},
{title:'Troubleshooting',icon:'🔧',content:'This is a quick-reference — the full Troubleshoot page (sidebar) has step-by-step guidance for these and more, all cider-specific.\n\nNo fermentation after 48h: Check temperature (Nottingham/M02 want 12-20°C), verify yeast wasn\'t killed by heat, add nutrient, swirl gently.\n\nCloudy cider that won\'t clear: Almost always pectin haze — if you skipped pectic enzyme, add it now rather than waiting on gravity alone. Perry is notoriously slower to clear than apple cider.\n\nSour / vinegar taste: Acetobacter (volatile acidity) — cider\'s single biggest real spoilage risk, especially in wild-fermented, low-sulfite styles. A light sulfite dose reduces the risk without losing much character.\n\nMousy off-flavor (only noticeable after swallowing): A cider-specific taint from certain lactic bacteria in low-sulfite, higher-pH cider. Sulfite promptly to stop it worsening.\n\nStuck fermentation: Warm up, add fresh Fermaid-O, repitch with EC-1118 for its higher alcohol tolerance.\n\nButtery/butterscotch flavor: In an English Cider deliberately pursuing malolactic fermentation, this IS the intended result — taste before treating it as a flaw.'},
{title:'Headspace by Stage',icon:'📐',content:'The same headspace principles as mead apply — the numbers barely change, since headspace is about foam/CO₂ physics, not what\'s fermenting.\n\n━━ Primary (9 L vessel) ━━\nFill to ~7 L (78% full) for a scaled-up batch, or proportionally for your recipe\'s actual volume. High-OG musts (New England, Ice Cider, Fire Cider) foam more vigorously and deserve the full headspace allowance.\n\n━━ Secondary (7.6 L or 5 L vessel) ━━\nSame approach as mead: 7.6 L at ~80% fill during active secondary, or straight into a 5 L vessel (~95% fill) once fermentation is nearly finished.\n\n━━ Bulk aging (5 L vessel) ━━\nFill as close to 100% as possible — oxygen exposure during long aging (English Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider, Fire Cider especially) is exactly as damaging to cider aromatics as it is to mead\'s.\n\nGENERAL RULES:\n• Primary NEEDS headspace (foam, CO₂).\n• Secondary WANTS less headspace once fermentation calms.\n• Bulk aging DEMANDS minimal headspace, especially for the long-aged styles.\n• Always rack gently under the surface — no splashing.'},
{title:'Bottling',icon:'🍾',content:'When to bottle: Two identical gravity readings a few days apart at the style\'s target FG (which may be quite sweet for Ice/Fire Cider, or bone dry for Sidra — check the recipe, don\'t assume).\n\nProcess: identical to mead — clean with Chemipro OXI, sanitize (Chemipro SAN or Star San), siphon (don\'t pour) into bottles, minimal headspace, cap immediately.\n\nUse the guided bottling workflow in the batch view — the same walkthrough mead uses (pre-flight, gravity check, sanitize timer, fill, label preview, final save) works identically for cider.\n\nStyle-specific timing reminders:\n• Common Cider, Fruit Cider, Spiced Cider: bottle and drink within weeks — these don\'t reward long cellar time.\n• Dry-Hopped Cider: bottle PROMPTLY — hop aroma fades with time even in the bottle, so this is the one style built to be enjoyed young rather than cellared.\n• English Cider, Applewine, Ice Cider, Fire Cider: these are the cider equivalent of mead\'s sack/high-ABV styles — built for the cellar, not the week after bottling.\n\nLabel each bottle: Batch name, date bottled, OG/FG, ABV, batch number — the same bottle label tooling works for both beverages.'},
{title:'Sparkling & Carbonated Cider',icon:'🍾',content:'Unlike mead — where a sparkling version is a deliberate special-case variant — sparkling is arguably the MORE traditional form of cider historically, especially in England\'s West Country and Normandy/Brittany. The same two routes and golden rule from mead apply, word for word.\n\n━━ THE GOLDEN RULE ━━\nBottle conditioning makes bubbles by feeding a small, measured dose of sugar to live yeast in a sealed bottle. You must NOT have stabilized: potassium sorbate + sulfite stop yeast from reproducing, and a stabilized cider will never carbonate naturally. Decide on sparkling BEFORE you stabilize.\n\n━━ FERMENT IT OUT FIRST ━━\nThe cider must be at a stable gravity (two identical readings several days apart) BEFORE priming — unless you\'re deliberately bottle-conditioning a cider still mid-ferment at a target sweetness (a riskier, more advanced technique). Leftover sugar + priming sugar + a sealed bottle = over-pressure and broken glass.\n\n━━ TARGET CARBONATION (CO₂ volumes) ━━\n• Still: under 0.5\n• Lightly sparkling / pétillant: ~1.5–2.0 (traditional for keeved French Cider specifically — real Asturian Sidra is traditionally still/flat, its effervescence coming from the dramatic escanciado pour-from-height ritual, not dissolved CO₂)\n• Sparkling: ~2.5\n• Champagne-style (Applewine especially suits this): ~3.5–4.0\n\n━━ METHOD 1 · BOTTLE CONDITIONING (priming) ━━\nUse Brewing Tools → Carbonation / Priming Sugar for the exact dose. Dissolve in a little warm water, mix in gently (no splashing), bottle in pressure-rated bottles, condition 2–3 weeks at 18–22°C.\n\n━━ METHOD 2 · FORCED CARBONATION (keg) ━━\nChill, set the regulator to the pressure for your target volumes, wait a few days. The only option for an already-stabilized cider.\n\n━━ BOTTLES & CLOSURES (safety) ━━\nStill-wine bottles are NOT pressure-rated. Use champagne/Belgian heavy bottles with crown caps or wired corks, or swing-top/heavy beer bottles for lower carbonation. Keep a clear PET tester bottle and condition inside a closed tub, just in case.\n\nSee Brewing Tools → Carbonation / Priming Sugar for the exact sugar dose and a pressure-safety check.'}
];}

// LABEL_IMAGES was previously a baked-in map of base64-encoded WebP images
